    <name>
				<text>35.4.4.8 Defective items from a production line</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<h4 class="HELM_exercise"> Exercise </h4>
<p> Machines \(M_A\) and \(M_B\) produce \({@pca@}\%\) and \({@pcb@}\%\) respectively of the production of a component intended for the motor industry. From experience, it is known that the probability that machine \(M_A\) produces a defective component is \(\displaystyle{{@dfa@}}\) while the probability that machine \(M_B\) produces a defective component is \(\displaystyle{{@dfb@}}\). If a component is selected at random from a dayâ€™s production and is found to be defective, find </p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li> \(p_A\), the probability that the item is from machine \(A\); </li>
<li> \(p_B\), the probability that the item is from machine \(B\). </li>
</ol>
<p> Give your probabilities as fractions, not decimals: </p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li> \(p_A=\quad\)[[input:ans1]][[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]] </li>
<li> \(p_B=\quad\)[[input:ans2]][[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]] </li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<h4 class="HELM_solution"> Solution </h4>
<p> Machines \(M_A\) and \(M_B\) produce \({@pca@}\%\) and \({@pcb@}\%\) respectively of the production of a component.</p><p>We know known that the probability that machine \(M_A\) produces a defective component is \(\displaystyle{{@dfa@}}\) while the probability that machine \(M_B\) produces a defective component is \(\displaystyle{{@dfb@}}\).</p><p>Let \(A = \{\text{item from machine }M_A\}\), \(B = \{\text{item from machine }M_B\}\), and \(D = \{\text{item is defective}\}\).&nbsp;</p><p>Then, the probabilities we have are \(\mathbb{P}(A) = \displaystyle {@pa@}\), \(\mathbb{P}(B) =\displaystyle {@pb@}\), \(\mathbb{P}(D|A) =\displaystyle {@dfa@}\) and \(\mathbb{P}(D|B) =\displaystyle {@dfb@}.\)</p><p>The probabilities we are looking for are \(p_A = \mathbb{P}(A|D)\) and \(p_B = \mathbb{P}(B|D)\) which can be found using Bayes' theorem: </p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li>\[\mathbb{P}(A|D) = \frac{\mathbb{P}(D|A)\mathbb{P}(A)}{\mathbb{P}(D|A)\mathbb{P}(A) + \mathbb{P}(D|B)\mathbb{P}(B)} = {@ta1@}. \] </li>
<li>\[\mathbb{P}(B|D) = \frac{\mathbb{P}(D|B)\mathbb{P}(B)}{\mathbb{P}(D|A)\mathbb{P}(A) + \mathbb{P}(D|B)\mathbb{P}(B)} = {@ta2@}. \] </li></ol>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
